    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:0a783a74-be27-4984-8337-c4b6112c7fb5",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 35-year-old man who appears fatigued and underweight, with visible temporal wasting and a persistent dry cough that occasionally becomes productive. He has intermittent fevers, drenching night sweats, and reports several weeks of progressive shortness of breath with exertion. During conversation he is alert and cooperative, but he pauses often to catch his breath and seems physically depleted. Mild cervical lymphadenopathy is present, and his clothes hang loosely after recent unintentional weight loss.\n\nHe works irregular hours as a restaurant line cook, a job he has struggled to maintain because of worsening stamina and frequent illness. Outside work, {patientName} used to play recreational soccer and spend weekends with friends, but lately he has become socially withdrawn and spends most of his free time resting at home. He lives alone in a small apartment, has limited financial reserves, and has missed several follow-up appointments in the past year because of transportation problems and unstable work scheduling.\n\nHis diet has become poor over recent months because of low appetite, fatigue, and chronic illness. He occasionally smokes cigarettes and drinks alcohol socially, and he reports prior inconsistent condom use with male partners. He has a small but supportive circle of friends and one sister who checks on him regularly, though he has not fully disclosed the extent of his illness to everyone close to him.\n\nOverall, {patientName} presents as a young adult with advanced HIV disease complicated by a mycobacterial opportunistic infection, with constitutional symptoms, respiratory complaints, and clear signs of chronic systemic illness affecting daily function and quality of life."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:6395b9eb-e1b1-43d2-a8c2-aedb1bf67733",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was diagnosed with HIV 4 years ago but has had inconsistent engagement in care and poor adherence to antiretroviral therapy during the past 18 months. He reports prior periods of doing well on treatment, followed by medication interruptions related to depression, unstable employment, and difficulty attending clinic appointments. Over the last 2 months, he has developed worsening fevers, night sweats, cough, and an 8 kg unintentional weight loss.\n\nHis past medical history includes recurrent oral candidiasis and one prior hospitalization 2 years ago for community-acquired pneumonia. He denies chronic kidney disease or diabetes. He smokes about half a pack of cigarettes per day and drinks alcohol on weekends. He has no known history of injection drug use, but he does report past high-risk sexual exposure. There is no known prior history of active tuberculosis treatment. The current presentation is concerning for advanced immunosuppression with HIV-associated mycobacterial pulmonary infection."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
